        <article class="post-detail">
            <header class="post-header">
                <span class="post-category">Technology</span>
                <h1 class="post-title">The Future of Web Development</h1>
                <div class="post-meta">Published on June 12, 2024 · 8 min read</div>
            </header>

            <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1555066931-4365d14bab8c?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxwaG90by1wYWdlfHx8fGVufDB8fHx8fA%3D%3D&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80" alt="Web Development" class="post-image">

            <div class="post-content">
                <p>Web development continues to evolve at a rapid pace, with new technologies and methodologies emerging constantly. This article explores the trends that are shaping the future of how we build for the web.</p>

                <h2>The Rise of AI-Assisted Development</h2>
                <p>Artificial intelligence is transforming how developers write code. Tools like GitHub Copilot suggest code snippets in real-time, potentially increasing productivity while raising questions about code originality and security.</p>

                <blockquote>
                    "The best developers of the future won't be those who can write the most code, but those who can most effectively leverage AI tools to solve problems." — Industry Expert
                </blockquote>

                <h2>WebAssembly (Wasm) Matures</h2>
                <p>WebAssembly allows code written in languages like C++, Rust, and Go to run in the browser at near-native speed. As Wasm matures, we're seeing:</p>

                <ul>
                    <li>Performance-intensive applications (photo/video editors, games) moving to the web</li>
                    <li>New possibilities for cross-platform development</li>
                    <li>Improved execution of legacy codebases in modern browsers</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Edge Computing Reshapes Architectures</h2>
                <p>The traditional client-server model is giving way to edge computing, where processing happens closer to the user. This means:</p>

                <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1620712943543-bcc4688e7485?ixlib=rb-4.0.3&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxwaG90by1wYWdlfHx8fGVufDB8fHx8fA%3D%3D&auto=format&fit=crop&w=800&q=80" alt="Edge Computing">

                <p>Reduced latency, improved privacy controls, and more resilient applications that can function with intermittent connectivity.</p>
            </div>

